name: Grilled Swordfish with Charred Leeks and Citrus

steps.instruction:
### Prep
- Coarsely chop the dill
- Prepare grill for high heat
- Trim dark part from the leeks and remove any of the tough layers 
- Rinse the leek

### Steps
1. Throw leeks on grill (no oil needed) and grill, turning every few minutes with tongs, until outside layer is completely blackened (they should start to soften and you might see some juices begin to ooze out), 10–12 minutes
2. Transfer to a platter and let cool (this also allows them to steam and become tender on the inside)
3. Reduce grill heat to medium-high
4. Meanwhile, smash open olives using the side of a chef’s knife and remove pits (try to leave olive flesh in big pieces)
5. Transfer to a medium bowl
6. Cut leeks into ½"-thick rounds (ashy parts and all) and add to bowl with olives along with dill, vinegar, a big pinch of salt, and 3 Tbsp. oil; toss to combine
7. Slice off both ends of oranges, exposing the flesh beneath the pith, then stand an orange upright on a cut side like this
![](https://assets.bonappetit.com/photos/5afc6f46ea709a36d0bf427f/master/w_1024/citrus-illo-1.jpg)
Following the natural curve of orange, slice away peel and white pith from top to bottom.
![](https://assets.bonappetit.com/photos/5afc6f4789a26c29083a94fd/master/w_1024/citrus-illo-2.jpg)
Trim off any remaining bits of pith, then lay orange on its side and cut crosswise into ¼"-thick rounds. Set aside for serving.
![](https://assets.bonappetit.com/photos/5afc6f49ea709a36d0bf4281/master/w_1024/citrus-illo-3.jpg)
7. Clean and oil grate and rub swordfish steaks with 2 Tbsp. oil; season with salt
8. Grill until lightly charred and just cooked through (fish will feel firm when gently pressed), 5–7 minutes per side
9. Divide swordfish among plates and arrange reserved sliced oranges around
10. Spoon leek mixture and any juices in bowl over
11. Drizzle with more oil and season with pepper
